  "biography_html": "<div class=\"research-section\">\n<p class=\"research-text\">Archimelus the Epigrammatist was a Greek poet of the Hellenistic period, generally placed in the 3rd century BCE based on stylistic evidence. No biographical details are recorded; his existence is known solely from his inclusion in the Greek Anthology.</p>\n<p class=\"research-text\">His two surviving works are dedicatory epigrams preserved in that collection. One is a two-line verse dedicating a bow to Apollo, and the other is a four-line epigram offering a fishing net to Poseidon.</p>\n<p class=\"research-text\">Archimelus exemplifies the tradition of minor Hellenistic epigrammatists. His brief, elegant poems are typical of the genre and contribute to understanding the period&#x27;s cultural and religious practices. His preservation within the Greek Anthology constitutes his primary historical significance.</p>\n</div>",
